This is an example of using Modules and Partials together to get a flexible component.

We arrive here either from _masthead.hbs, or from any template that needs to display this partial in a unique manner.

The context passed to this partial should match what exists in masthead.json under fixtures.

Everything here is an example and not a strict guideline on how to form the markup for modules and partials. Just understand
that the JSON data in the fixture should match between the one for the module and the context being passed from a template.

An example:

masthead.json
{
	"title": "Masthead",
	"caption": "This is a masthead caption",
	"img": "/img/masthead.png"
}

template.json
{
	masthead: {
		"title": "This template's masthead",
		"caption": "A different caption",
		"img": "/img/level-masthead.png"
	}
}

_masthead.hbs (this is the module)
{{! 	<!-- module:masthead -->
{{! 	{{#parseFixture 'masthead.json'}}
{{! 		{{> masthead }}
{{! 	{{/parseFixture}}
{{! 	<!-- end module:masthead -->

template.hbs (This will render the partial version of the masthead using the template's data)
{{!		<main>
{{!
{{! 		{{#parseFixture 'template.json'}}
{{! 			{{> masthead masthead }}
{{! 		{{/parseFixture}}
{{!
{{! 	</main>

template2.hbs (This will render the module version of the masthead)
{{!		<main>
{{!
{{! 		{{> _masthead }}
{{!
{{! 	</main>

}} -->
<figure class="masthead">

	<div class="image" style="background-image: url('{{img}}');"></div>

	<figcaption class="masthead__caption">
		<p>{{caption}}</p>
	</figcaption>

</figure>
